**Solution Explanation**

For every pair of sparkling points we can compute the Euclidean distance

\[
d(P_i , P_j)=\sqrt{(x_i-x_j)^2+(y_i-y_j)^2 } .
\]

The task is to output the largest of all these distances.

Because the number of points can be large (up to \(10^5\) in the test data), a
straight‑forward \(O(N^2)\) scan of all pairs would be too slow.
The maximum distance between two points of a set is called the *diameter* of
the set.  
The diameter is always realised by two vertices of the convex hull of the
points.  
Therefore we can

1. build the convex hull of the input points – \(O(N\log N)\);
2. find the farthest pair of hull vertices with the rotating‑calipers
   technique – \(O(H)\) where \(H\) is the number of hull vertices
   (\(H\le N\)).

The algorithm is well known and runs fast enough for the given limits.



--------------------------------------------------------------------

#### Algorithm
```
read N
read all N points

if N == 1
        answer = 0
else
        // 1. Convex hull (Monotone chain)
        sort points by (x, y)
        build lower hull
        build upper hull
        concatenate, removing the last point of each part
        let hull[0 … H-1] be the resulting list

        // 2. Rotating calipers – diameter of the hull
        if H == 2
                answer = distance between hull[0] and hull[1]
        else
                j = 1
                maxSq = 0
                for i = 0 … H-1
                        next = (i+1) mod H
                        // move j while area increases
                        while area(hull[i], hull[next], hull[(j+1) mod H]) >
                              area(hull[i], hull[next], hull[j])
                                j = (j+1) mod H
                        // update maximum distance
                        maxSq = max(maxSq,
                                    distSq(hull[i], hull[j]),
                                    distSq(hull[next], hull[j]))
                answer = sqrt(maxSq)

output "Final Answer: " followed by answer with 6 digits after the decimal point
```

*`area(a,b,c)`* is the absolute value of the cross product  
\((b-a)\times(c-a)\); it is used to decide whether the distance to the
next point is larger.

--------------------------------------------------------------------

#### Correctness Proof  

We prove that the algorithm outputs the maximum possible distance between
any two sparkling points.

---

##### Lemma 1  
The maximum distance between two points of a set equals the maximum distance
between two vertices of its convex hull.

**Proof.**

Let \(P\) be the set of all points and \(H\) its convex hull.
Every point of \(P\) lies inside or on the boundary of \(H\).
For any two points \(p,q\in P\) the segment \(\overline{pq}\) lies inside
\(H\).  
If \(p\) or \(q\) is not a vertex of \(H\), we can replace it by a vertex
of \(H\) that lies on the same side of the segment and does not shorten the
segment.  
Thus a pair of vertices of \(H\) achieves at least the same distance as
any pair of points of \(P\).  
Conversely, vertices of \(H\) are points of \(P\), so the maximum over
vertices cannot exceed the maximum over all points. ∎



##### Lemma 2  
The rotating‑calipers procedure described above visits, for every edge
\(\overline{h_i h_{i+1}}\) of the convex hull, the farthest vertex
\(h_j\) from that edge.

**Proof.**

For a convex polygon the function  
\(f(j)=\text{area}(h_i,h_{i+1},h_j)\) is unimodal in \(j\) (it increases,
reaches a maximum, then decreases).  
The while‑loop moves \(j\) forward as long as the area increases, therefore
after the loop terminates \(j\) is at a local maximum of \(f\), i.e. the
vertex farthest from the directed edge \(\overline{h_i h_{i+1}}\). ∎



##### Lemma 3  
During the loop over all edges the algorithm considers every antipodal pair
of hull vertices.

**Proof.**

An antipodal pair is a pair of vertices that are farthest apart in the
direction of some edge of the hull.  
By Lemma&nbsp;2, for each edge the algorithm examines the farthest vertex
\(h_j\) from that edge.  
The pair \((h_i,h_j)\) (and also \((h_{i+1},h_j)\)) is therefore an
antipodal pair.  
All antipodal pairs are examined because the loop iterates over all edges
of the hull. ∎



##### Lemma 4  
`maxSq` computed by the algorithm equals the square of the diameter of the
convex hull.

**Proof.**

By Lemma&nbsp;3 every antipodal pair is examined, and for each such pair
the squared distance is compared with `maxSq`.  
The diameter is the maximum distance over all pairs of hull vertices, and
every such pair is either an antipodal pair or can be transformed into one
by rotating the calipers.  
Hence the maximum squared distance found by the algorithm equals the
diameter squared. ∎



##### Theorem  
The algorithm outputs the maximum possible distance between two sparkling
points.

**Proof.**

By Lemma&nbsp;1 the maximum distance over all points equals the diameter of
the convex hull.  
By Lemma&nbsp;4 the algorithm computes exactly this diameter (after taking
the square root).  
Therefore the printed value is the required maximum distance. ∎



--------------------------------------------------------------------

#### Complexity Analysis

Let \(N\) be the number of input points and \(H\) the number of hull
vertices (\(H \le N\)).

*Sorting* – \(O(N\log N)\)  
*Building the hull* – \(O(N)\)  
*Rotating calipers* – \(O(H)\)  

Overall time complexity: **\(O(N\log N)\)**.  
Memory usage: the list of points and the hull – **\(O(N)\)**.



--------------------------------------------------------------------

#### Reference Implementation  (C++17)

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

struct Point {
    long long x, y;
    bool operator<(const Point& other) const {
        if (x != other.x) return x < other.x;
        return y < other.y;
    }
};

long long cross(const Point& O, const Point& A, const Point& B) {
    return (A.x - O.x) * (B.y - O.y) - (A.y - O.y) * (B.x - O.x);
}

long long distSq(const Point& A, const Point& B) {
    long long dx = A.x - B.x;
    long long dy = A.y - B.y;
    return dx * dx + dy * dy;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int N;
    if (!(cin >> N)) return 0;
    vector<Point> pts(N);
    for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i) cin >> pts[i].x >> pts[i].y;

    if (N <= 1) {
        cout << "Final Answer: 0.000000\n";
        return 0;
    }

    sort(pts.begin(), pts.end());

    // Build convex hull (Monotone chain)
    vector<Point> hull;
    // lower hull
    for (const auto& p : pts) {
        while (hull.size() >= 2 &&
               cross(hull[hull.size()-2], hull.back(), p) <= 0)
            hull.pop_back();
        hull.push_back(p);
    }
    // upper hull
    size_t t = hull.size() + 1;
    for (int i = N-2; i >= 0; --i) {
        const auto& p = pts[i];
        while (hull.size() >= t &&
               cross(hull[hull.size()-2], hull.back(), p) <= 0)
            hull.pop_back();
        hull.push_back(p);
    }
    hull.pop_back(); // last point is same as first

    int H = hull.size();
    if (H == 2) {
        double ans = sqrt((double)distSq(hull[0], hull[1]));
        cout.setf(ios::fixed); cout << setprecision(6);
        cout << "Final Answer: " << ans << "\n";
        return 0;
    }

    // Rotating calipers
    long long maxSq = 0;
    int j = 1;
    for (int i = 0; i < H; ++i) {
        int ni = (i + 1) % H;
        // move j while area increases
        while (abs(cross(hull[i], hull[ni], hull[(j + 1) % H])) >
               abs(cross(hull[i], hull[ni], hull[j])))
            j = (j + 1) % H;
        maxSq = max(maxSq, distSq(hull[i], hull[j]));
        maxSq = max(maxSq, distSq(hull[ni], hull[j]));
    }

    double answer = sqrt((double)maxSq);
    cout.setf(ios::fixed);
    cout << setprecision(6);
    cout << "Final Answer: " << answer << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

The program follows exactly the algorithm proven correct above and
conforms to the required output format.

